         <PROCEDURE>
            <PT_AWARD_CONTRACT_WITHOUT_CALL>
               <D_OUTSIDE_SCOPE/>
               <D_JUSTIFICATION>
                  <P>The Combined Heat and Power Plant (CHP) situated at Fellside focusses on the safety critical function of providing steam to Sellafield site. CHP is an ageing fragile facility near the end of its design life. Sellafield undertook a review of current and future site steam requirements, the Sellafield Site Steam Strategy, concluding that future steam delivery for site operations will be via two Steam Generation Plants (SGP) currently due to be fully operational by 2021. CHP operations will be required until replacement by these new facilities following which CHP will be wound down in preparation for decommissioning and demolition. The strategy from CHP to boiler only operations necessitates an extension of the contractual arrangements with the current CHP ops and maintenance provider until March 2021. Extension of the current arrangements have taken place by way of a new contract with the existing provider PX Limited to safely ensure continued operations of CHP which, given the age of the facility requires ongoing significant care, repair and maintenance. This will include undertaking key activities for plant upgrades to comply with Industrial Emissions Directive (2010/75/EU), and provision of care and maintenance of aged and obsolete equipment. The first SGP is due to be commissioned in spring 2018 with PX heavily involved in key transitional activities leading to full operations. It was determined that in the circumstances competition to deliver the services was absent for technical reasons and that, pursuant to Article 32(2)(b)(II) of Directive 2014/24/EU and Regulation 32(2)(b)(II) of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015, Sellafield may award a contract to PX using the negotiated procedure without prior publication of a contract notice in the Official Journal. In particular, based upon our assessment of the market and feedback, Sellafield considered that there was no practical alternative to continuing to engage PX to deliver steam and provide care, repair and maintenance services. Given, in particular, that PX is the only organisation with detailed understanding of CHP and Sellafield’s specific technical and operational requirements necessary to ensure safe and effective provision of services. Engaging a substitute provider would have carried very significant operational risks for Sellafield. Once the 2 new SGP’s are commissioned and in operation, Sellafield intends to bring to the market the opportunity to operate and maintain the two new SGP’s.</P>
               </D_JUSTIFICATION>
            </PT_AWARD_CONTRACT_WITHOUT_CALL>
